This logic is flawed when there is an overflow.
Reproducer:
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args){
        withNanos();
        withMillis();
    }

    private static void withMillis() {
        long start = TimeUnit.NANOSECONDS.toMillis(Long.MAX_VALUE-10);
        long end = TimeUnit.NANOSECONDS.toMillis(Long.MAX_VALUE+1);
        long delta = end-start;
        System.out.println("delta "+delta+" ms");
    }

    private static void withNanos() {
        long start = Long.MAX_VALUE-10;
        long end = Long.MAX_VALUE+1;
        long delta = end-start;
        System.out.println("delta: "+delta+" ns");
    }
}

delta: 11 ns
delta -18446744073708 ms

if nanotime is dealt with correctly it deals gracefully with overflow. Also keep in mind that nanotime can start at an arbitrary value; so in theory the returned value could be close to Long.MAX_VALUE and you could run into the overflow very quickly.

